New Christmas single out today featuring @astynturr and @isa_ma_music called “We Bow.” 

Of all the cultural practices I’ve encountered in my years of traveling the world, the one that I really wish was part of my own culture is bowing. When I first went to Japan, and felt what it was like for people to bow to each other, it was so beautiful to honor and revere the life inside one another like that.  Years later, I learned what has become one of my favorite meditation techniques from the teachings of Sadhguru—just subtly bowing to reality throughout your day. There’s something so heart opening about it. The divine in me recognizes itself around me. As we began to enter the holiday season, I thought of Christmas and the story of Jesus. I thought about the story of shepherds bowing before this poor little refugee baby in a manger, and how the incomprehensible mystery of existence experiences itself within the tiny and mundane. And it made me want to bow.

This is a voice memo from when I was alone one night in the studio while recording the “Love Song to Life” album after all the other musicians had left. I just pushed record without knowing what I was going to do to see if any magic came out. (Sometimes songs get written that way for me.) But what came out was this old church song from growing up.

I started crying while playing it. Not out of sadness but out of overwhelming love and gratitude for life and the journey I’ve been on. While the “you” in “there is none like you” is no longer a guy “out there” somewhere in my imagination, I was so happy to be able to be able to sing this song like this again with my full heart. There were a lot of years I wouldn’t have been able to.

As I sit here in this backyard, I can feel the weight of memories bearing down on me. This is the place where my girls grew up, where we laughed and played and danced in the rain. It's where we held barbecues with friends and family, and where we watched the stars twinkle above us on warm summer nights. Hundreds of songs and podcasts were recorded here. Two books were written here. 

But now, as I sit here one last time, I know that we must leave this place. Our family can no longer afford to live here, and we must say goodbye to this home that has been such an important part of our lives.

It's been hard our family to let go of something that has been so integral to our story and community. This house has seen us through countless milestones and memories, and it's where we created a home that was filled with love, laughter, and joy. And plenty of tears too, of course. 

As I take one last look around, I can see the evidence of our life here. The trees we planted. The play house where our girls have laughed and played, and the hot tub where we shared countless deep and absurd conversations.

But as hard as it is to leave, I know that our memories and the love that we shared here will always be with us. Our family's story will continue to unfold, and we will create new memories and milestones in whatever new home we find. 

So as I say goodbye to this backyard and this home, I do so with gratitude and love in my heart for what this place has been for us. It may be bittersweet, but I know that our family will carry the love and memories of this place with us wherever we go.

One critique of the work I’ve done in the last several years has been one of cultural appropriation. Whether it was around the spiritual name “Vishnu Dass” that Ram Dass gave me before he died, or even just interviewing a master swami like Sally Kempton (who happened to be white) on this last Liturgists podcast, there have often been comments or emails that accuse us of cultural appropriation. 

Funny enough, I never got emails accusing me of Jewish or Italian (Roman Catholic) appropriation when our content was exclusively Christian, but we can save that for another time. For now, I just want to narrow in on the observation that one would only make such an accusation if one assumed the elements of those spiritualities to be untrue. It’s one thing to wear a burka for a Halloween costume… It’s quite another to find keys to the very nature of Reality through various practices and spiritual technologies that were discovered by people who live on a different side of history or of the globe than you do.  Accusations of appropriation in that context may seem on the surface to be progressive and generous, but they are actually quite condescending and arrogantly dismissive of both truth and the people that were instrumental in that truth’s transmission and discovery.

I’m doing these looping things because I’ve noticed that there are sort of two sides to creating stuff—

1. Raw creative output (spirit, flow, chaos) [the Feminine]
2. Editing [the Masculine]

If you don’t know how to tap into both sides of that equation, you will be very limited in the scope of your creative work. These improv sessions are an exercise for me in totally turning off the editor in my head and just flowing with whatever happens. In the short time I’ve been doing it, I’ve found it useful and already gotten one song out of these sessions that I’m really happy with and have fully recorded (and edited) already. So this is just me welcoming you into my creative process and behind the scenes chaos of my musical life. Honored to share space with you 🕺🏽🩵

Anybody know of a church open to “heretics” like me? After so many years of journeying through different practices and religious explorations, I’m feeling ready to plant some roots in a specific community/tradition in order to find some more synergy and play in making this world a more beautiful place. But I need that community to be one open enough theologically and energetically to have room for someone like me who doesn’t believe in any sort of religious exclusivity to participate fully with all of my being (not just my giving and attendance). Do such communities or churches exist? If so, please tell me about them!
We had a good time

I’ve been getting a ton of comments on a post from this last week about searching for a church that wasn’t exclusive of other religions. In the last couple days specifically, a lot of the comments have been around this idea of exclusivity. I understand and empathize with this view to a certain extent because I too was raised to believe that there was one path to God—Jesus Christ. 

I was taught that any other path was idolatry. But what if idolatry isn’t about picking the wrong God as much as believing God to be limited to one specific thing? What if the real issue with the Israelites making a golden calf in the Old Testament wasn’t that God couldn’t be found in gold or in crafted images, but in their belief that God was EXCLUSIVELY found in some sort of crafted image?

I thought God needed some sort of exclusive path among many to be followed, but over time I found that god to be quite small and finite—a human creation. An idol. 

Some people have been very effective at marketing the gospel of Jesus as some sort of exclusive water bottle—the one and only one that will quench your thirst! But it is Water that quenches thirst, not fancy, exclusive water bottles. Water is exclusive, yes. Water is the only way to quenched thirst. And there is only one Water.

That video I posted the other day about looking for a church has over 250k views already and close to a thousand comments. Why?! I don’t quite understand it, but I do suspect that :

1- I think I have underestimated how much people care about church and overestimated how much they care about theology

2-I think there are probably a lot of people out there asking some of these same questions and longing for a spiritual community that accepts them as they are as well. 

Thoughts?

I’ve heard several Christians through the years use this verse in 2 Timothy 4:3 to support their bigotry or closed mindedness. The verse says “For the time will come when people will not put up with sound doctrine. Instead, to suit their own desires, they will gather around them a great number of teachers to say what their itching ears want to hear. They will turn their ears away from the truth and turn aside to myths.” 

My question—what if the false gospel that tickles the ego’s ears is precisely closed off one that holds itself to be the one and only truth over everyone else’s views? What if that gospel of fear that is always accusing other views of being idolatrous IS THE IDOLATRY? What if that exclusive view of God being on OUR side and that the Bible is the only source of truth is precisely the kind idolatrous, fear based, ego tickling nonsense that Timothy warned about?

I’ve been having such great convos this week with a lot of you who have watched my post about church shopping or listened to the podcast about it. One idea that sometimes trips people up is the idea that being inclusive means that you don’t get to have any of your own specific convictions or beliefs, and that’s simply not true. 

Being inclusive doesn’t mean you don’t get to be you. It just means that while being exactly as you are, you are humble and open handed enough to allow others to be exactly as they are well. 

Being inclusive isn’t some progressive ideology that demands any specific beliefs. It’s just being humble and loving. 

“But it’s not loving to leave people in their sin!” (I can anticipate the angry commenter saying)

I think Jesus might respond to that something like “let the person without sin cast the first stone.” Maybe we could focus on our own sin, not theirs. Maybe we could focus on our own convictions and staying true to them, and stop trying to be the savior for everybody else.
A meditation to bring us into Unity

It’s so easy and tempting to look at where we used to be with disdain and where we haven’t yet gone with fear. If we get curious about these feelings in ourselves, allowing ourselves to fully feel them while exploring what’s inside of them, they can be a tremendous grace for us in walking into more love, freedom and consciousness in our lives. If however, we take the easy way out and become a victim (my feeling is because THEY…) or a staunch “believer” in our current position and justify the fear as a legitimate concern about a slippery slope or something, we miss the opportunity that life is presenting us with.

There are always two sides to every war-humans vs beliefs. 

Countries were made for people—not people for countries. Religion was made for people-not people for religion. I stand on the side of people. 

If it has a heartbeat, it’s not the enemy. 

The enemies are the beliefs that we have in our heads that make us bomb, rape, kidnap and murder each other. War is just mass murder. Every human life is sacred. 

Land doesn’t belong to people. We belong to the earth. We are all one human family. #peace #ceasefire

Confession: I’ve never been a Swiftie. But the Taylor Swift Era’s tour at my local AMC IMAX this Sunday was surprisingly for me an incredibly beautiful and sacred experience. And given that I’ve been church shopping lately, it has me thinking about what was so special about that experience and how it relates to community and how and why people gather together. 

I’m a music snob. And in my estimation, there are so many people who have more technical ability in singing, playing, and dancing than Taylor. (Though her performance was admittedly way more impressive in all of these respects than I had expected.) But with her, it’s more than the technical or raw talent. She is an amazing songwriter, yes, but there are a lot of amazing songwriters. But with her, it’s all of this together, but even that isn’t quite it. There’s something about her that feels, I don’t know… authentic. Her flirtation with the audience. Her being herself so completely through so many years. Why is it that one of us actually being unapologetically us creates such fervor and love in others? And why is this apparently so rare? And why does it seem to be especially rare in “spiritual” spaces?

Why can singing about one’s own demons in a dark theatre with strangers feel more angelic than singing “holy, holy” with angels painted on the walls? 

Don’t get me wrong, I’m not hating on church here. Imm also not saying I need church to be like a Taylor Swift concert. I’m simply wondering how those of us who want to have meaningful and authentic community can learn from a beautiful experience like this concert was to be more authentic and free with one another. How can we create spaces and music and rituals that celebrate the whole journey of life like Taylor is so beautifully doing with this tour? I think people are hungry to be together. To sing. To dance. To share friendship bracelets. I just think that’s worth noticing.

#taylorswift #erastour #church

Some of you might remember this musical idea from several months back. Well, my @onearthmusic partner @tylerchester and I have finally finished producing it and it will be out Friday everywhere you listen to your music

Today, we are thrilled to share a new song called “Lonely Road” from On Earth.

On Earth began from music that we (Michael Gungor and Tyler Chester) were scoring together for the Liturgists Podcast. We wanted music that was heart opening without being full on synth pad meditation music. Music that had some movement and melody but that could work as a score to life without being too distracting. Music that would be nice to read to or take a walk in the moonlight with. And that’s the vibe we’ve stayed with. We hear a lot of people like listening to On Earth while they work or do homework or even while they get ready to sleep.

In times like these, when the world seems to be engulfed in discord, it may feel futile to seek solace in the melodies we create. But perhaps it is precisely during these moments that we need the power of music the most.

While it may seem like a small act, dwelling in peace and tranquility personally can have a profound ripple effect on the world around us. Just as the proverbial flap of a butterfly’s wings can set in motion a cascade of changes, our individual choices to embrace peace within ourselves can reverberate far beyond our immediate surroundings.

So more than just inviting you to listen to our new song “Lonely Road” (which we hope you will), our deeper invitation and encouragement to you today would be to immerse yourself in as much peace and beauty as you can find. Score your life in a way today that reverberates with love. Stillness. Serenity. Joy. 
As you dwell in and as peace today, your very presence becomes a sort of vibration holder or prayer that has the potential to touch lives far beyond yourself.

Listen, dwell, and be at peace today, not only for yourself but for all of us. Together, let us make a difference, one breath, one little melody at a time.

Ok, so vulnerable moment here.. This voice memo is pretty raw. But it was sort of a pivotal moment for me, and I wanted to share it with you. 

A year and a half ago, while writing for the Love Song to Life record, I sat down at the piano and pushed record to see what new music might come of it.  Instead of any new music coming out, I was surprised by the immediate arising of an old worship song that I used to sing as a kid. As the old familiar words flowed out of my suddenly shaky and emotional vocal cords, a profound sense of peace and love overwhelmed me and the tears quickly began to flow as well. 

I’ve gone through a lot of twists and turns in my life and career. I grew up as a pastors kid, and then became a successful Christian worship leader and recording artist. Just as my career was  really starting to hit big though, I went through a lot of doubt and spiritual searching that left a lot of my life and career in shambles. 

Sitting there at that piano somewhere in Texas all by myself in the middle of the night trying to think of what kind of music I want to make now after all of those years of seeking and evolving, I could feel so clearly and deeply how it’s always only been God.  Every single moment of it. I could rise to the heavens or make my bed in the place of the dead, and thou art with me. 

Throughout life’s twists and turns, we often overlook the Presence that has been with us all along. This voice memo is a reminder that amidst all our apparent wandering, we are always cradled in the unwavering love of the Divine. While it may not be of the highest quality technically speaking, there’s something sort of bloody and raw about it that iI like—something that feels like my soul.

I hope this reminds you that no matter where you’re at on your journey, Love’s got you. Ask every question. Live every adventure. Love’s got you.

Thank you All Saints and every other spiritual group or organization who is risking sticking your neck out and speaking up for all the children being slaughtered in Gaza right now. #ceasefire Thank you for caring for the human beings on all sides of all the conflicts and for standing for life. Thanks for calling us look at what’s uncomfortable to look at and to live and love in the manner of the one who Christians claim to follow. You have helped give me some hope for what church can be in the world.

In my quest for a local church as of late, I have been wonderfully surprised at how open-minded and inclusive a lot of the people have been. Even the preaching! But when it comes to music… I’ve noticed it (and heard from lots of pastors and worship leaders) that it can be difficult sometimes to find songs that are singable, musical AND theologically kind. 
	
So I’ve decided to start a project that I’m calling “Mystic Hymnal” that is an effort to meet some of those needs. I’m looking for collaborators right now, and I’ll tell you more about it soon.  But just letting you know what’s coming.
Some more info on this “Mystic Hymnal” idea

A mystic is someone who remembers their Being (also called “the presence of God”). From the contemplative silence of Meister Eckhart to the ecstatic poems of St. Teresa of Avila, the mystical thread of Christianity has been spun with golden moments of divine encounter.

Mystics like St. John of the Cross and Julian of Norwich charted the inner landscapes of the soul, finding God’s Life as pervasive and complete.

While this thread has never been the predominant or mainstream aspect of Christendom, I personally believe it is the directly transmitted Gospel that was passed through history starting from Christ himself.

While the empire of Christendom has always focused on using the past to control the future, the mystical thread is all about Now.

I sometimes hear bits of this thread in places where the charismatic fervor of worship ignites the same ancient longing for the ‘Presence of God.’ In every lifted hand and every chorus that fills our sanctuaries, we echo the mystics’ call to experience the Divine intimately, to know the Love that dances as everything and everyone.

Because this thread has often been encased in human ego—fear, shame, oppression...etc., many of us have had to leave those spaces, but some of us have inadvertently thrown out the baby with the bathwater.

For those of you who may have had experiences of “the presence of God” before… Can you remember what that is like? It feels like a dissolving of my will into the Divine. It feels like surrender. Freedom. Infinite Love. This is what other traditions call enlightenment, satori, moksha…etc.

What if it’s possible to not have to learn a different language or mythical framework in order to dwell in this space that the Psalmist described as “better is one day in your courts than a thousand elsewhere”?

Perhaps if we focus more on the Spirit that is here and now rather than our ideas and beliefs about history or the future—if we focus a little more on the Word of God that is being spoken right now through every tree, every thought, every breath, than in old books, we might discover what the mystics saw.

#MysticalChristianity #PresenceOfGod #CharismaticWorship #DivineEncounter #spiritualheritage

January 20, some friends and I are launching a new event that reimagines what communal singing or “worship” can be. Don’t worry, this video clip isn’t our answer to that question.. but lighthearted, childlike wonder is definitely a significant part of it. 

“Play” is a fun, healing, and mystical “worship” event intended to help us remember who we are together. “Play” is not your typical worship event as we are not trying to get anyone to believe anything or to or be any way other than they already are. But we do love to use the power of communal singing to connect, heal, and celebrate the divine Life that unites us all underneath our masks and stories.  The universal language of music is at the heart of how we commune together, and there are three rules for the songs we sing at “Play”: it needs to be musically captivating; easily singable for newcomers; and theologically kind (rooted in unity and love, fostering a sense of togetherness.) 

In an attempt to make this event as accessible as possible to those who might be struggling financially right now (which is a lot of us), we have decided to make the RSVP for this event free. (If you are in a secure financial position, and you’d like to help us cover some of the costs of these events, we will gratefully accept loving donations.) 

Throughout 2024, we have planned a series of events, beginning with an in-person gathering on January 20. For more info, or to RSVP for what promises to be a magical and unforgettable night of loving, healing connection, click the link in my bio. Hope to see you there!
“A WRETCH like me??” No thanks. Working on the set list for “Play” on January 20th (RSVP link in bio, and thinking about doing a rendition of Amazing Grace with some lyric changes.

In what has become a fairly predictable pattern on my posts, the conversation on my last post was lovely and thoughtful for the first few days, and then this morning, the pack of angry religious people who for some reason follow me around sometimes come along and fill the post with invective and nonsense. I will ignore most of it, but this is just a reminder to anyone who might be wondering if the small minded judgmental religious world that believes themselves to be Christians really have the full story, or even an accurate view of Christ’s gospel—they don’t. 

Any “gospel” that says you are anything less than the Beloved or the image of God is a perversion of the gospel. 

Someone telling you that you are a “wretch” and then saying that’s part of the good news is engaging more in gaslighting and blasphemy then in preaching the message that the Prince of Peace taught.

The Good News is—you are enough as you are now. Nothing is missing. You are seen and loved completely already. This is why we can look at the birds or the flowers without worrying about tomorrow. It’s why we can afford to take up our crosses and die. Because we are already unified with Love. And this is why you will know Christ’s disciples by their love, and not by their caustic, Bible-worshipping, shame-serving, beauty-despising idolatry that they call Christianity.

The only place you can ever find Truth is within your Self. 

The entire idea of “authority” is an illusion because even if you project your sense of authority to someone or something else, you are still the one doing that.  Like a child projecting their anger through their toys, so many of us give our power and agency away to some big “Other”. If THEY (God, the Bible, the political party, the scientist…etc) said it, then I don’t have to worry about its moral or ethical implications. I don’t have to use my own brain or stay in contact with my own heart or conscience.

I’m not saying we can’t trust others or rely on people who are wiser or more learned in certain areas than we are. But we would do well to acknowledge that this is what we are doing. We are lending them our own authority. We are not giving it to them. We couldn’t ever actually give it to them. We could only try to forget that we lent it. Don’t forget. No one else can live your life but you. No one else can point to true North. Only your own heart/soul/body can be the final authority on that.
